#. HTML: </p><h1>
#. VAR: 12. Gūthakhādasutta → gūthakhādi-duṭṭhabrāhmaṇo (pts1-2)
msgctxt "sn19.12:0.3"
msgid "12. Gūthakhādasutta "
msgstr "12. A Dung Eater "

#. HTML: </h1></div><p>
#. REF: sc1
msgctxt "sn19.12:1.1"
msgid "“Idhāhaṃ, āvuso, gijjhakūṭā pabbatā orohanto addasaṃ purisaṃ gūthakūpe nimuggaṃ ubhohi hatthehi gūthaṃ khādantaṃ … pe … "
msgstr "“Just now, reverend, as I was descending from Vulture’s Peak Mountain I saw a man sunk in a sewer, eating dung with both hands. …” … "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "sn19.12:1.2"
msgid "eso, bhikkhave, satto imasmiṃyeva rājagahe duṭṭhabrāhmaṇo ahosi. "
msgstr "“That being used to be a nasty brahmin right here in Rājagaha. "

# NOTE: BB has “rice pot” for doniya. But in the suttas it is used for a feeding trough for horses; a casket for a corpse; and a pan for working gold, etc. Here “trough” clearly fits.
#. VAR: doṇiyo → doṇiyā (s1-3, km, pts1-2, mr)
msgctxt "sn19.12:1.3"
msgid "So kassapassa sammāsambuddhassa pāvacane bhikkhusaṃghaṃ bhattena nimantetvā doṇiyo gūthassa pūrāpetvā etadavoca—"
msgstr "In the time of the Buddha Kassapa’s dispensation he invited the Saṅgha of mendicants for a meal. He filled a trough with dung and said: "

msgctxt "sn19.12:1.4"
msgid "aho bhonto yāvadatthaṃ bhuñjantu ceva harantu cā’ti … pe …. "
msgstr "‘My good men, eat as much as you like, and take what’s left.’ …” "

#. HTML: </p><p class="endsection">
msgctxt "sn19.12:1.5"
msgid "Dutiyaṃ. "
msgstr ""

